{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608228"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:30:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:30:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15992"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15992"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8683"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63443"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8683"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15992"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48896"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7113"},{"type":"tags","id":"8663"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20784"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63443"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryonic development, the human brain undergoes several important flexures. One of these is rostral flexion, where the developing forebrain grows and rotates relative to surrounding cranial structures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the degree of rotation that occurs during rostral flexion of the forebrain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["45 degrees","90 degrees","180 degrees","270 degrees","360 degrees"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryonic development, \u003Cstrong\u003E180 degrees\u003C/strong\u003E of rotation occurs during rostral flexion. This significant rotation is necessary to establish the proper anatomical relationships between the forebrain and other cranial structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E45 degrees\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient rotation to achieve proper anatomical positioning\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E90 degrees\u003C/strong\u003E would only position the forebrain at a right angle, which is inadequate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E270 degrees\u003C/strong\u003E would result in excessive rotation beyond what is necessary\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E360 degrees\u003C/strong\u003E would complete a full rotation, returning structures to their original position\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis 180-degree rotation brings cranial structures to a position caudal to the forebrain, establishing the basic adult anatomical arrangement of these structures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["During embryonic development, rostral flexion causes the forebrain to rotate 180 degrees relative to other cranial structures.","Rostral flexion is a critical developmental process that establishes the proper anatomical relationship between the forebrain and other cranial structures."],"references":["Wilson SW, Houart C. Early steps in the development of the forebrain. Dev Cell. 2004 Feb;6(2):167-81. doi: 10.1016/s1534-5807(04)00027-9. PMID: 14960272; PMCID: PMC2789258.","Gaillard R, Steegers EA, de Jongste JC, Hofman A, Jaddoe VW. Tracking of fetal growth characteristics during different trimesters and the risks of adverse birth outcomes. Int J Epidemiol. 2014 Aug;43(4):1140-53. doi: 10.1093/ije/dyu036. Epub 2014 Mar 5. PMID: 24603318; PMCID: PMC4258770","Chen X, Liu H, Li Y, Zhang W, Zhou A, Xia W, Xu S. First-trimester fetal size, accelerated growth in utero, and child neurodevelopment in a cohort study. BMC Med. 2024 Apr 29;22(1):181. doi: 10.1186/s12916-024-03390-3. PMID: 38685041; PMCID: PMC11059611","Godfrey KM, Inskip HM, Hanson MA. The long-term effects of prenatal development on growth and metabolism. Semin Reprod Med. 2011 May;29(3):257-65. doi: 10.1055/s-0031-1275518. Epub 2011 Jul 18. PMID: 21769765; PMCID: PMC3685133","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48896"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15992"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48896"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T22:50:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T22:14:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8683"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63443"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://ap